/*

Two ways to make highlighted text darker.

Was doing:

body: {color: #2b2b2b;}
#highlight: {mix-blend-mode: multiply; pointer-events: none;}

(With highlight z-index not set, same level as everything else.)

Now doing:

body {color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.83);}
#highlight {z-index: -1;}

Old way resulted in:
unhighlight text: rgb(43, 43, 43)
highlighted text rgb(43, 42, 41)

New way results in:
unhighlighed text: rgb(47, 47, 47)
highlighted text: rgb(47, 47, 45)

Can't seem to get new way value any closer to old way values.
Tried tweaking the alpha setting of the text color (0.835, etc.),
but it doesn't seem to be very fine grained.

New way advantages:
Some browsers don't support mix-blend-mode.

Old way advantages:
Liked it slightly darker.

*/

bg-color = #fff
text-color = #2b2b2b
highlight-color = #fffbf1

body
  background bg-color
  color text-color
  font-family 'Linux Libertine', serif
  font-feature-settings 'kern', 'liga', 'clig', 'onum' 1
  margin 0
  background-image linear-gradient(#eee 1px, transparent 1px)
  background-size 100% 12px

#text
  max-width 528px
  margin 0 auto
  
#highlight
  position absolute
  background highlight-color
  z-index -1
  /* mix-blend-mode multiply
  pointer-events none */
  
p
  margin 0
  padding 0

.seg
  text-align center
  font-size 36px
  line-height 48px
  padding 12px 24px

.note
  text-align justify
  font-size 24px
  line-height 36px
  padding 24px 0 0 0 /* Also looks good with 24px on left and right */
  hyphens auto /* Doesn't work in Chrome and others */

.hide
  display none